1. What is a Bipartite Graph?

Answer:
A bipartite graph is a graph whose vertices can be divided into two disjoint sets such that every edge connects a vertex from one set to a vertex in the other set. No two vertices in the same set are connected.

2. What are the rules of a Bipartite Graph?

Answer:

Vertices are divided into two sets.
Edges can exist only between the two sets.
No edge can connect two vertices within the same set.
3. Give a real-world example of a Bipartite Graph.

Answer:
Students and Courses.

Students form one set.
Courses form another set.
An edge represents a student enrolled in a course.

